summary.name: GitHubActivity
summary.dataset_description: A dataset containing the number of GitHub activities per hour between January 1, 2015, and May 30, 2015.

properties.description: The timestamp of the recorded GitHub activity, in hourly intervals.
The number of GitHub activities recorded during the corresponding hour.

goals.question: What is the overall trend of GitHub activities during the given time period?
goals.visualization: Line chart of count vs time
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is an overall increase or decrease in GitHub activities over time.

goals.question: What is the distribution of GitHub activities per hour?
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the range of GitHub activities per hour and if there are any outliers.

goals.question: What is the average number of GitHub activities per day?
goals.visualization: Bar chart of average count per day
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the average number of GitHub activities per day and if there are any days with significantly higher or lower activity.

goals.question: What is the busiest hour of the day for GitHub activities?
goals.visualization: Line chart of count vs time of day
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand the peak hours of GitHub activities and if there are any patterns in the activity throughout the day.

goals.question: What is the correlation between the number of GitHub activities and the day of the week?
goals.visualization: Scatter plot of count vs day of the week
goals.rationale: This visualization will help us understand if there is any correlation between the number of GitHub activities and the day of the week, and if certain days have higher or lower activity.

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['time'] = pd.to_datetime(data['time'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['time'])]

    plt.figure(figsize=(12, 6))
    sns.lineplot(x='time', y='count', data=data, legend='brief')
    plt.title('What is the overall trend of GitHub activities during the given time period?', wrap=True)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.xlabel('Time')
    plt.ylabel('GitHub Activities Count')
    plt.legend(title='GitHub Activities', loc='upper left')

    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['time'] = pd.to_datetime(data['time'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['time'])]
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.histplot(data=data, x='count', bins=20, color='blue', kde=True)
    plt.axvline(data['count'].median(), color='red', linestyle='--', label=f"Median: {data['count'].median():.2f}")
    plt.xlabel('GitHub Activities per Hour')
    plt.ylabel('Frequency')
    plt.title('What is the distribution of GitHub activities per hour?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['time'] = pd.to_datetime(data['time'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['time'])]
    data['day'] = data['time'].dt.date
    daily_average = data.groupby('day')['count'].mean().reset_index()

    ax = sns.barplot(x='day', y='count', data=daily_average)
    plt.xticks(rotation=45)
    plt.title('What is the average number of GitHub activities per day?', wrap=True)
    plt.xlabel('Day')
    plt.ylabel('Average Count')
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['time'] = pd.to_datetime(data['time'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['time'])]
    data['hour'] = data['time'].dt.hour

    hourly_counts = data.groupby('hour')['count'].mean().reset_index()

    max_hour = hourly_counts.loc[hourly_counts['count'].idxmax(), 'hour']
    max_count = hourly_counts.loc[hourly_counts['count'].idxmax(), 'count']

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.lineplot(x='hour', y='count', data=hourly_counts)
    plt.axvline(x=max_hour, color='r', linestyle='--', label=f'Max: {max_hour} ({max_count:.2f})')
    plt.xlabel('Hour of the Day')
    plt.ylabel('Average GitHub Activities')
    plt.title('What is the busiest hour of the day for GitHub activities?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend()
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)

import seaborn as sns
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

def plot(data: pd.DataFrame):
    data['time'] = pd.to_datetime(data['time'], errors='coerce')
    data = data[pd.notna(data['time'])]
    data['day_of_week'] = data['time'].dt.dayofweek

    plt.figure(figsize=(10, 6))
    sns.scatterplot(x='day_of_week', y='count', data=data, hue='day_of_week', palette='viridis', legend='full')
    plt.xticks(np.arange(0, 7, 1), ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday'], rotation=45)
    plt.xlabel('Day of the Week')
    plt.ylabel('Number of GitHub Activities')
    plt.title('What is the correlation between the number of GitHub activities and the day of the week?', wrap=True)
    plt.legend(title='Day of the Week', loc='upper right')
    
    return plt;

chart = plot(data)
